<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-078-806  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 078 806.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Jan 22 1990 v24 n4 p10(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Ontyme users not in the loop? (British Telecommunications PLC'srestructuring may move Tymnet's Ontyme electronic mail service toDialcom)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Horwitt, Elisabeth.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>British Telecommunications PLC is merging the technical and humanresources of its Dialcom electronic mail service division withTymnet's electronic mail and value-added networking services.andP;  Theformation of the new company, BT Tymnet Inc, caused the layoff of240 employees across Dialcom and Tymnet, but the new company hasnot kept customers informed of the planned changes.andP;  One customerwas told by his Tymnet account representative about the mergerafter spending six months reworking the company's pricingstructure on the existing Ontyme system.andP;  The accountrepresentative was laid off soon after, leaving the customer withno representative to contact in case of a billing problem orsystem change request.andP;  Users of Dialcom seem to be betterinformed about changes in the offing and less concerned about thenew setup; BT plans to maintain service on both systems until themerger is completed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   British Telecommunications PLC (customer relations)Tymnet Inc. (acquisitions and mergers)BT Tymnet Inc. (services).andO;Topic:     Communications Service SuppliersCustomer RelationsMergerAcquisitionElectronic mail systemsOntyme (Electronic mail system)Dialcom (Electronic mail system).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>